Project Foundations for Data Science: FoodHub Data Analysis¶

Marks: 40

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

The trends are the same, there is no logical reason to think that there is a relationship between delivery time and cost of the order with the presence/absence of rankings.¶

It is logical that not all orders have a rating since this is usually optional in delivery services. Moreover, there is not a relation between the orders without ratings with their cuisine type, cost of delivery or delivery time, which implies that it is just random. Let's treat the missing values with the mean rating of their respective cuisine.¶

In [534]:
#First we make every "Not given" value into a NumPy NaN
df["rating"].replace("Not given", np.nan, inplace=True)

# Then we make every object an int
df["rating"] = pd.to_numeric(df["rating"])

# Then we transform the missing values with the mean value of their respective cuisine type
df["rating"] = df["rating"].fillna(value = df.groupby(["cuisine_type"])["rating"].transform("mean"))

# We then make them categorical again
df["rating"] = df["rating"].astype(int).astype(str)
print(df["rating"].value_counts())

rating
4    1122
5     588
3     188
Name: count, dtype: int64
By doing this we got rid of the missing values. Someone could argue that it would be better to leave them like they are, but also the method implemented is a good practice.¶

Question 9: What percentage of the orders costs more than 20 dollars?¶

In [543]:
# We define variables for all the parameters that will be relevant.
costs = df["cost_of_the_order"]
mu = costs.mean()
s = costs.std()
minimum = costs.min()
maximum = costs.max()
n = costs.shape[0]

# We find the percentage using the cumulative distribution function assuming normality since n is big (CLT).
print("Percentage more than 20 USD:", str(round((1 - stats.norm.cdf(20, mu, s))*100,3)) + "%\n")


# For visualization purposes:
# We create our x-axis vector based on the minimum, maximum and n variables.
x1 = np.linspace(minimum - 10, maximum + 5, n)
# We create our density function
costs_function = stats.norm.pdf(x=x1, loc = mu, scale = s)

# The red area is created for visualization purposes.
plt.axvline(20, color="red")
x2 = np.linspace(20, maximum + 5, 50)
plt.fill_between(x2, stats.norm.pdf(x2, mu, s), color="r")

#The plot is created
plt.plot(x1, costs_function)
plt.show()

Percentage more than 20 USD: 31.995%
Almost a third of the orders cost more than 20 USD.¶

Question 13: The company wants to provide a promotional offer in the advertisement of the restaurants. The condition to get the offer is that the restaurants must have a rating count of more than 50 and the average rating should be greater than 4. Find the restaurants fulfilling the criteria to get the promotional offer¶

In [552]:
# We first create a copy considering only the orders wit a given rating. Then we transform the ratings into type int.
find_promotion_df = df_original[df_original["rating"] != "Not given"].copy()
find_promotion_df["rating"] = find_promotion_df["rating"].astype(int)

# We find those restaurants with more than 50 given ratings.
fifty_ratings = find_promotion_df["restaurant_name"].value_counts()
fifty_ratings = fifty_ratings[fifty_ratings > 50]

# We find those restaurants with more than 4 given rating average.
greater_than_4 = find_promotion_df[find_promotion_df["rating"] != "Not given"].groupby("restaurant_name")["rating"].mean()
greater_than_4 = greater_than_4[greater_than_4 > 4]

# We concatenate both pandas Series on the condition that a given index exist in  both Series ("inner join")
promotion_restaurants = pd.concat([fifty_ratings, greater_than_4], axis=1, join='inner')
print(promotion_restaurants)

Question 14: The company charges the restaurant 25% on the orders having cost greater than 20 dollars and 15% on the orders having cost greater than 5 dollars. Find the net revenue generated by the company across all orders¶

In [553]:
# We define our accumulator to find the total revenue
total_revenue = 0

# We find the orders in the range of prices of 5 < row <= 20
between_5_and_20_df = df[(df["cost_of_the_order"] > 5) & (df["cost_of_the_order"] <= 20)]
# We add this revenue to our variable.
total_revenue += (between_5_and_20_df["cost_of_the_order"]*0.15).sum()

# We find the orders in the range of prices of 5 < row <= 20
more_tan_20_df = df[df["cost_of_the_order"] > 20]
# We add this revenue to our variable.
total_revenue += (more_tan_20_df["cost_of_the_order"]*0.25).sum()

print("The net revenue generated by the company across all orders is: $" + str(round(total_revenue,2)) + " USD.")

The net revenue generated by the company across all orders is: $6166.3 USD.
The company has generated $6166.3 USD from these 2 conditions¶

Question 15: The company wants to analyze the total time required to deliver the food. What percentage of orders take more than 60 minutes to get delivered from the time the order is placed? (The food has to be prepared and then delivered)¶

In [554]:
# We define variables for all the parameters that will be relevant.
total_time = df["total_time"]
mu = total_time.mean()
s = total_time.std()
minimum = total_time.min()
maximum = total_time.max()
n = total_time.shape[0]

# We find the percentage using the cumulative distribution function assuming normality since n is big (CLT).
print("Percentage more than 60 minutes:", str(round((1 - stats.norm.cdf(60, mu, s))*100,3)) + "%\n")


# For visualization purposes:
# We create our x-axis vector based on the minimum, maximum and n variables.
x1 = np.linspace(minimum - 10, maximum + 5, n)
# We create our density function
total_time_function = stats.norm.pdf(x=x1, loc = mu, scale = s)

# The red area is created for visualization purposes.
plt.axvline(60, color="orange")
x2 = np.linspace(60, maximum + 5, 50)
plt.fill_between(x2, stats.norm.pdf(x2, mu, s), color="orange")

#The plot is created
plt.plot(x1, total_time_function)
plt.show()

Percentage more than 60 minutes: 10.769%
Only 10.77% of the orders take more than one hour to be delivered.¶

Conclusion and Recommendations¶

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations)¶

Conclusions:¶

  • The app is used a lot of the weekends and it works quite well since deliveries
  • 98.9% of clients have ordered less than 6 times.
  • The top 5 restaurants represent 33% of the orders.
  • Bad ratings are given on weekends when the total delivery time is high.
  • The Indian Cuisine customers leave the most reviews
  • The French Cuisine has the highest median order cost.

Recommendations:¶

  • American, Japanese and Italian cuisines are cash cows. Therefore, it is reasonable to contact more local restaurants of these cuisines to give clients more options (maybe closer to their house). Even if ratings don't always depend on the delivery time, it has been shown that low ratings are given when the delivery time is high on weekends.
  • The French cuisine could be advertised more. It has the highest median cost and has potential to be exploited more. Maybe give some advertisement to it.
  • Since 5 restaurants represent 1/3 of the income, they could be charged a bit more or discuss with them a win-win situation since clearly the app is being beneficial to those restaurants.
  • Clients don't use the app more than 6 times. Maybe it would be benefitial to consider if the GUI is simple. Additionally, a smart notification/reward system could be used so that clients place more orders.
  • A market study could be held related to Indian Cuisine orders, since the custoemrs leave more often than not a review. It might be that it is something to do with the package of the delivery or the demographics of the customers. This traits could be exploited so that other customers also leave reviews.
  • More promotions could appear on weekdays to boost profits, since currently most happen on the weekends.
  • Some Cuisines like Korean and Vietnamese have only a few orders and with small margins. Maybe it is a matter of location or simply the product is not as good. It could be a good idea to reduce focus in these cuisines and boost other mid-range cuisines like Mexican or Chinese.
